CLINICAL HISTORY: 32 year old male with episodes of bilateral hand shaking and
loss of awareness. These episodes stopped after the patient began Depakote therapy.
MEDICATIONS: Depakote
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic
simulation were preformed. This was a 1 hour sleep-deprived study.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a 9.5 Hz posterior dominant
rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background slowing and anterior
spread of the alpha rhythm. Hyperventilation produces a small degree of background
slowing. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR: 66 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features were identified in this
EEG nor in the previous EEG. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   49 year old left handed male with migraine headaches and visual scintillations.  Head trauma.

MEDICATIONS:  Enalapril, Zocor, Glucosamine, ASA, Insulin

INTRODUCTION:   Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are preformed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:   In wakefulness, background EEG includes a well organized 10 hertz alpha rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness produces an increase in background theta. POSTS are observed in stage I sleep. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving. The patient drifts back into stage I sleep.

HR: 	60 bpm

IMPRESSION:   Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features were identified.

CLINICAL HISTORY:	69 year old  right handed male, with recurrent episodes of lightheadedness lasting 4 hours, multiple medical problems.

MEDICATIONS: Zocor, Quinine, Cardura


INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was not performed, but photic stimulation was completed.  This is an awake and a sleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In maximal wakefulness there is an 8.5 Hz alpha rhythm. Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic background slowing. Photic stimulation was performed as the patient is drifting off to sleep and does not activate the record.

HR: 90 bpm


IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.


CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features were observed.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  53 year old right handed male with head trauma in 1982, now losing track of time, depression,  anxiety, forgetfulness. Episodes of forgetfulness increasing in stress but none for the last month.
MEDICATIONS: Metformin, Glyburide, Actoplus, Aceon
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness the background EEG is well organized with 10 Hz 40 mcv posterior dominant rhythm. Occasional temporal wicket is observed. The patient transitions in and out of stage 2 sleep with vertex waves and spindles.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background followed by drowsiness.  More extensive stage 2 sleep with vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles are observed later on in the record. Photic stimulation elicits a driving response at faster flash frequencies.
HR:	78 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. The wicket activity described above is a normal variant.

CLINICAL HISTORY:	62 year old woman with hallucinations, CHF.


MEDICATIONS:  Neurontin, Metoprolol, Renagel, ASA, PhosLo


INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was not performed, but photic simulation was completed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9 hertz posterior dominant rhythm. Lambda waves are observed in the background. There is a generous amount of low voltage frontocentral beta activity and muscle artifact as the patient is not particularly cooperative. Features of drowsiness include an increase in background slowing, occasional vertex waves are observed. Photic stimulation elicits a subtle
driving response.


HR:	96 bpm


IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.


CLINICAL CORRELATION:   No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. Normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. Lambda waves are a normal phenomenon.

CLINICAL HISTORY:	22  year old right handed male with epilepsy characterized by loss of consciousness and shivering, seizure free for 2 months. Past history of asthma.

MEDICATIONS:  Dilantin

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed.  This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10.5 Hz posterior dominant rhythm with alpha squeak. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR:   66 bpm

CLINICAL HISTORY:  52 year old right handed woman with a loss of consciousness this past Monday, hypersomnolence today prior to thyroidectomy. Ongoing confusion.
MEDICATIONS: Ventolin, Albuterol.
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The majority of the record includes stage II  sleep with vertex, K complexes and spindles.  Little testing is performed to assess for cognitive testing.  The patient is stimulated and when she is awake, the background includes a well-defined, 9.5 Hz alpha rhythm.
HR:	84 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG demonstrates an excessively sleepy individual but normal awake through stage II sleep.  Morphology or wave forms are noted. Additional evaluation for the cause for her excessive drowsiness might be appropriate.

CLINICAL HISTORY:	31 year old man with history of generalized tonic clonic activity during sleep with post ictal unresponsiveness x 3-5 minutes.
MEDICATIONS:  None
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  This is a very drowsy study. The patient drifts in and out of sleep during the entirety of the study. He does have a background alpha rhythm of 11 Hz. There is also the presence of POSTS, and slow rolling eye movements. During photic stimulation, there is a mild driving response until the patient falls asleep.  Hyperventilation creates an increased amplitude.
HR:	72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There is no epileptiform activity. This was an otherwise normal EEG. Drowsiness may be related to sleep-deprived EEG, however the sleep is not sustained. This may be related to a sleep disorder. Normal EEG's do not exclude epilepsy. Based on clinical correlation, a repeat EEG may be warranted to find focal
features.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   25 year old woman 8 months pregnancy with epilepsy since age
18.  The last tonic clonic seizure was in August 2009 during sleep. MEDICATIONS:  None
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Photic stimulation is performed. This an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background EEG includes a 10 Hz 30 microvolt alpha rhythm.   Drowsiness is characterized by generous beta.  Beta spindles, vertex waves, and POSTS are identified in stage II sleep. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR: 	96 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are identified in this awake and asleep EEG.  After this the patient delivers her infant, additional EEG recording with activation techniques may be helpful to characterize epileptiform activity. Alternatively, comparison with previous EEG's may also be beneficial.  The generous beta activity could be associated with medications or anxiety.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   37 year old right handed male with recurrent black out spells lasting 10-15 seconds when the patient looses awareness of his surroundings.   No incontinence.   No tonic clonic activity.
MEDICATIONS: None
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.   This is an awake and a sleep record
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:   In wakefulness  there is a 10 Hz 40 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of low voltage, frontal central beta activity.  Drowsiness is characterized  by an increase in beta and anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained. Hyperventilation does not activate the record. Photic stimulation does elicit bilateral driving.
HR: 	84 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG in wakefulness and brief drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed, but if epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat study capturing deeper stages of sleep should be considered.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 45 year old right handed woman with epilepsy, seizure 2 weeks ago characterized by tongue biting and confusion. History of diabetes, hypertension, and asthma.
MEDICATIONS: Keppra
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed. This is an awake and a sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively low voltage, particularly for an adult of this age. There is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm identified and central MU rhythm is observed, but testing it not performed to confirm this. Features of drowsiness include rhythmic background slowing. Photic stimulation elicits lambda. POSTS are observed in sleep.
HR: 60 bpm
IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features are observed. Additional
recording, either sleep deprived or using other techniques may be helpful to characterize epileptiform activity.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 54 year old woman with tonic colonic seizures, seizure free for the last 3 years.
MEDICATIONS: Dilantin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are-performed. This is an awake and sleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively low voltage, but there is a discernible 10.5 Hz alpha rhythm in a background of generous beta. Much of the record includes drowsiness with attenuation of the alpha rhythm. Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the record. Photic stimulation does elicit a driving response.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG is within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were noted. The features described above, including the low voltage pattern and scant alpha are not pathologic in this age group. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat study may be considered, particularly when capturing deeper stages of sleep.

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy. Fortunately, given the neurologic problems described above, there was no background slowing seen and no focal pathology observed.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation are performed. This is an awake and asleep record.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the overall background is relatively low voltage with a scant, 8 Hz alpha rhythm and generous beta. Hyperventilation is performed early in the record producing an increase in the amplitude of the background. Following hyperventilation as the patient drifts off to sleep, there is an increase in beta, rare bursts of temporal slowing followed by vertex waves and posts. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.

HR: 72 bpm

IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed in this record. This EEG is within the limits of normal. It is overall a lower voltage pattern. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a follow-up study may be considered. In addition, repeat studies may be helpful in monitoring the patient's cerebral pattern in the context of dementia/delirium.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Photic simulation is performed. This is an awake and asleep record.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 9.5 Hz, 85 microvolt posterior dominant rhythm with a small amount of posterior slow waves. Drowsiness is characterized by rhythmic theta followed by vertex waves in stage I sleep. Brief epochs of stage II sleep with bursts of K-complexes and spindles are interrupted with an awake pattern. Head rocking artifact is picked up particularly in the posterior regions. Photic stimulation elicits a scant driving response. Some electrode artifacts and pops are noted during photic.
HR: 78 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: There is some head rocking artifact noted in the occipital scalp regions but no epileptiform features were noted.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 72 year old right handed male with right arm weakness,

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed at bedside using standard 1 0-?0
system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The patient is drowsy throughout much of the
record. In maximal wakefulness there is an 8.8 Hz alpha rhythm. Drowsiness is

artifact in the right frontotemporal region.
HR: 96 bpm
IMPRESSION: This EEG is at the limits of normal for an adult of this age.

wakefulness the overall background is acceptable for an adult of this age. If epilepsy is

CLINICAL HISTORY: 62 year old right handed male with seizure like spells August
2009 characterized by eyes open, shaking lasting seconds. Throat cancer, coughing
and supplemental oxygen requirements.
MEDICATIONS: Metformin, Pilocarpine, Diovan, Simvastatin, Dilantin
INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20
system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG. Hyperventilation was not
performed, but photic simulation is performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, the background EEG is well
organized with a low voltage of 9 hertz alpha rhythm .and a generous amount of low
voltage, frontocentral beta activity. Drowsiness is characterized by an increase in beta.
In the transition to drowsiness, there is some shifting slowing particularly in the right
central region. Photic stimulation elicits bilateral driving.
HR: 90 bpm
IMPRESSION: EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No epileptiform features were observed. There is some
occasional age related shifting slowing in drowsiness, but none outside of the limits of
normal. This is the patient's second EEG without epileptiform activity. If there are strong
concerns about seizures, a more prolonged sleep EEG or an overnight recording may
be of use. The shifting and slowing identified in drowsiness is a nonspecific finding and
can be seen in the context of underlying cerebrovascular disease or simply as a normal
finding in a senior citizen.

LONG TERM MONITORING - 07/07/2010 - 10-68

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness, there is a 10Hz alpha rhythm. Stage II sleep is characterized by vertex waves and spindles.

Event:
Time 21:39:05. the patient is awake, watching television. She is eating an apple. The EEG demonstrates a normal and awake pattern. The nurse comes in and tests the patient who is coherent. There are no epileptiform features noted.

LONG TERM MONITORING - 07-08-2010 - 10-68

INTRODUCTION: Continuous digital video EEG monitoring is performed in the unit using the standard 1 0-20 system of electrode placement with one-channel EKG. This section of the record includes sleep deprivation. The patient reports an aura characterized by headache and dizziness but has none of her spells with shaking.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: The background EEG includes well-organized 10 Hz alpha rhythm. Stage II sleep includes vertex waves, K complexes, and spindles. The computerized seizure and spike detections are reviewed. No epileptiform features are identified at that time. The time samples in question were reviewed. No epileptiform findings were noted. In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm. Stage II sleep is characterized by vertex waves and spindles.

Event:
Time 21 :39:05. the patient is awake, watching television. She is eating an apple. The EEG demonstrates a normal and awake pattern. The nurse comes in and tests the patient who is coherent. There are no epileptiform features noted.

HR: 60 to 80 bpm.

IMPRESSION: This EEG monitoring is remarkable for:
1. Two events characterized by an aura, one of which had a push-button and neither which had an EEG signature.
2. Norma148-hour EEG without epileptiform activity.
3. An inability to record one of her shaking spells.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: A normal EEG was seen during her 2007 long-term monitoring period. Behaviors at that time were not associated with epileptiform activity. If capturing one of this patients shaking spells is needed, please consider an outpatient ambulatory EEG.

CLINICAL HISTORY: 35 year old right handed female with blackout spells for the last 2 years occurring 1-3 times a year and migraine headaches 2-4 times per week. This is an outpatient EEG.

MEDICATIONS: Unknown.

INTRODUCTION: Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG. Hyperventilation and photic simulation were performed.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD: In wakefulness there is a low voltage g Hertz posterior dominant rhythm. The patient transitions rapidly into stage 1 and stage 2 sleep with rhythmic central theta followed by vertex waves, K-complexes, spindles and posts. Abrupt arousals are noted in and out of stage 2 sleep with at that point a 10 point 7 Hertz alpha rhythm. Hyperventilation does not activate the record. Photic stimulation elicits a vigorous driving response with harmonic and supra harmonic driving.

HR: 72bpm

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.

CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are observed. The transitions in and out of sleep are not necessarily indicative of any sort of pathology and can be seen in somebody who is a light sleeper, sleep deprived or has difficulty consolidating sleep.

IMPRESSION: Normal EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION: No focal nor epileptiform features are identified. The supraharmonic driving is a normal variant. If epilepsy is an important consideration, a repeat study may be considered.

DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The background demonstrates a very nervous individual with almost continuous eye blinking.  When he stops, there is an 8.7 Hz alpha rhythm.  Hyperventilation produces a small amount of slowing.  Photic stimulation elicits scant driving.
HR:    78 bpm
IMPRESSION:   EEG is within normal limits in wakefulness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There were no epileptiform features identified.  Additional evaluation with sleep could be considered if the patient is able to relax.  The frequent eye blink can be seen in nervousness.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  31 year old right handed woman with intermittent episodes of lightheadedness and palpitations.
MEDICATIONS:  Metoprolol
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 9.7 Hz alpha rhythm which is symmetric and reactive to eye opening.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in amplitude of the background.  Features of drowsiness include an increase in rhythmicity of the background as well as anterior spread of the alpha rhythm.  A single burst of paroxysmal rhythmic slowing is noted if the patient transitions to sleep but then photic stimulation is performed. The rare bursts of hypersynchronous slowing are noted in photic stimulation, but unfortunately this does seem to collide with the attempt to capture sleep.
HR:    72 bpm
IMPRESSION:  EEG within normal limits.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  Hypnagogic hypersynchrony is a normal variant.  If additional information is needed, a 1-hour study which does not need to be sleep
deprived but just simply to capture sleep may be helpful, if there are any additional questions.

CLINICAL HISTORY:   32 year old right handed male with chief complaint of staring spells, last month having an episode of loss of consciousness and woke up shaking.  He also has numbness in his hands and legs.
MEDICATIONS:  Xanax, Percocet, Tylenol No. 3.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with 1 channel EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, there is a 10 Hz alpha rhythm with generous beta.  In relaxed wakefulness there are occasional single channel artifacts.
Features of sleep include attenuation of the alpha and the appearance of beta activity, as well as some theta.  Deeper stages of sleep are not sustained.  Hyperventilation produces an increase in theta. Photic stimulation elicits scant driving and a background already rich in beta frequency activity.
HR:    48 bpm
IMPRESSION:  Normal EEG with bradycardia.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  There were no epileptiform features identified.  A normal EEG does not exclude a diagnosis of epilepsy.  If seizures are an important consideration, a follow up study is suggested.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  56 year old right handed male with recurrent right focal seizures and right-sided numbness with new left parietal lesion on CT.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  49 year old right handed female with seizures since age 14, presents with refractory episodes, here for seizure classification.
MEDICATIONS:  Keppra.
REASON FOR STUDY:  Seizures.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in lab using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrodes.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness.  Hyperventilation was performed.
TECHNICAL DIFFICULTIES:  None.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm of 9 to 10 Hz, which is reactive to eye opening.  There is an increased amount of beta activity seen diffusely throughout the EEG.  During the recording, the patient is recorded only during wakefulness.  The only activating procedure that is performed is hyperventilation, during which she has an episode which I will describe below.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
Events:  During this recording, while the patient was doing hyperventilation she suddenly stopped responding, started moving her throat and jerking her back and forth repeatedly.  At times she would move to the left and then to the right.  During this episode, the tech stimulated her feet and she would respond and at times appeared to follow commands, but would not verbalize.  The whole episode of unresponsiveness lasted some minutes, but with the clinical presentation lasted about 12 minutes.  During this recording, the EEG revealed prominent muscle artifact but a nice posterior dominant rhythm could be seen at times and normal EEG could be seen at times throughout the episode.
SEIZURES:  None.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake EEG with an episode of unresponsiveness as described above with no EEG correlate.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This EEG is diagnostic of a nonepileptic event, likely psychogenic in nature.  Otherwise this is a normal awake EEG and no seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.

DIAGNOSIS:  Rule out seizures.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 19-year-old woman with a family history of epilepsy who presents with episodes described as foot shaking, stomach jumping, feeling of dizziness, and hot.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  A digital EEG was performed in the lab  using the standard International 10-20 system of electrode placement in addition to one channel of EKG monitoring.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.  This tracing captures wakefulness only.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In the most alert state, the alpha rhythm is 9 to 10 Hz in frequency, 30 to 40 microvolt in amplitude seen the occipital region which attenuates with eye opening.  There is a small amount of low amplitude frontocentral beta activity which is distributed symmetrically.  Hyperventilation results in symmetric slowing of the background.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple/frequencies and resulted in a symmetric driving response.  Heart rate is 60 to 70 beats per minute and regular.
CLINICAL EVENTS:  A 10:00:43 the patient reported that she has an attack described as her stomach is jumping with her arm on top of it.  She added that this is part of her attack.  At 10:06:01 she reported that she is feeling hot.  At 10:11:54 she stated that she is seeing blinking red stuff that hurts.  EEG showed a normal awake pattern with a posterior dominant rhythm of 9 to 10 Hz.  Eye blink artifact, lateral eye movement artifacts and muscle artifact with no epileptiform activity during this event.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG recording capturing wakefulness only.  No epileptiform abnormalities were identified in this record.  The episodes were characterized by clinical events of jumping stomach, feeling hot, and seeing blinking red stuff without any significant EEG correlation.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This study does not support the diagnosis of epilepsy.  The episodes are diagnostic for psychogenic nonepileptiform events.  Although this study does not exclude the possibility of epilepsy and intermittent seizures, if seizures are a clinical concern a prolonged ambulatory EEG may be helpful to capture other types of events.

LENGTH OF RECORDING:  22 minutes.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 61-year-old man with a recent pontine hemorrhage, now with worsening mental status since this a.m., 01/02/2013.  EEG is performed since there is a possibility of nonconvulsive status epilepticus.
CURRENT MEDICATIONS:  Tylenol, Colace, ciprofloxacin, nystatin.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were not performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  Voltages are diffusely low.  The posterior dominant rhythm over the left hemisphere consists of low amplitude 8-9 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient over the left hemisphere with faster frequencies at lower amplitudes anteriorly.  There is nearly continuous EMG artifact over the right hemispheric leads that obscures most of the right hemispheric recording.  No sleep architecture is observed.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are not performed.
FINDINGS:
Nearly continuous EMG artifact over the right hemispheric leads that obscures those leads.  This EMG artifact makes interpretation of the activity over the right hemisphere not reliable.
No clear epileptiform discharges.
No electrographic seizures.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake only 22-minute EEG.  There is nearly continuous EMG artifact over the right hemispheric leads that obscures significant portions of the recording over the right hemispheric leads.  Therefore, interpretation of the background over the right hemisphere is not reliable.  If concern for seizures persists, a repeat study with less EMG artifact may be of benefit.  No clear electrographic seizures are captured.

REASON FOR STUDIES:  Seizures.

INTRODUCTION:  A routine EEG was performed using standard 10-20 electrode placement system with additional anterior temporal and single-lead EKG electrode.  The patient was recorded during wakefulness.  Activating procedures included hyperventilation and photic stimulation.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The record opens to a well-defined posterior dominant rhythm that reaches 9 Hz which is reactive to eye opening.  There is an excessive amount of beta throughout the recording.  The patient is recorded in wakefulness and drowsiness.
The heart rate is 54.
ABNORMAL DISCHARGES:  None.
EPISODES:
During the recording as photic stimulation was being performed the patient started stuttering and her right arm started shaking and trembling for a period of 11 minutes.  The patient is responsive throughout the whole period; however, the code word which she was asked to memorize and later asked to repeat was repeated incorrectly at the end of the event.  During this event the EEG appeared to be normal with no epileptiform activity seen or EEG correlate seen.
IMPRESSION:  Normal awake and drowsy EEG.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy EEG.  No seizures or epileptiform discharges were seen.  The episode described above, which started on with the right arm shaking did not reveal any EEG correlate, as such it may represent a nonepileptic event or alternatively it may be a simple partial seizure, which in up to 75% of the cases do not have any EEG correlate.  Lastly, please note that the excessive beta noted on the EEG may be due to a medication effect.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 54-year-old male with history of head trauma and diffuse axonal brain injury, who reports fall.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  This is a 56-year-old right-handed female with a complaint of a syncopal event on March 25, 2013.  Apparently she fainted and was on the floor for 15 seconds and then was observed to shake.  Of note, during the recording here in the laboratory, there was a brief episode of right hemibody tingling.
MEDICATIONS:
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG is performed in the lab/bedside using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation are performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  The recording start time was 11:29 a.m.  The recording end time was 12 noon.  The recording length was 25 minutes.
As the record opens there is a well formed and symmetric 9-10 Hz  posterior dominant rhythm that is reactive to eye opening.  There is a small amount of frontal central beta activity that is symmetrically distributed.  Brief drowsiness is characterized by attenuation and fragmentation of the posterior dominant rhythm.  At approximately 11:45 a.m., approximately 15 minutes into the recording epic, the patient complained of right hemibody tingling and numbness.  She was examined by the physician in the laboratory at the time, and there were no obvious clinical sequela.  During this time, there was no change in the background cerebral activity of the EEG.
Hyperventilation was performed for 3 minutes with good effort and failed to activate the tracing.  Photic stimulation was performed at multiple flash frequencies and induced a very reactive and responsive photic driving response at intermediate flash frequency ranges.  The patient's heart rate ranged from 70-90 beats during the record epic.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG capturing wakefulness and drowsiness.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  A normal EEG does no rule out a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  The brief clinical event of right hemibody numbness and tingling were not associated with changes in the background cerebral activity.  Thus, this event is likely a nonepileptic event.

Step photic stimulation results in symmetrical occipital driving at multiple flash frequencies.
FINDINGS:
No stage 2 sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
Blinking artifact.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and drowsy 21-minute EEG.  No epileptiform discharges were captured, however, stage 2 sleep was not recorded.  If clinical indications for seizures persist, a repeat study with stage 2 sleep may be of benefit.  Frequent blinking artifact is captured throughout the recording.  This could limit interpretation of the activity over the right frontal regions.

CLINICAL HISTORY:  A 62-year-old man had an unwitnessed seizure in a car.  The patient is amnestic for the event.  He has a 1 year history of blackouts. He stopped drinking after seizure on May 13.
MEDICATIONS:  Unknown.
INTRODUCTION:  Digital video EEG was performed in the lab using standard 10-20 system of electrode placement with one channel of EKG.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were completed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORD:  In wakefulness, the background EEG is relatively low voltage, but there is a symmetric, reactive, 8.5 Hz alpha rhythm.  Drowsiness was characterized by attenuation of the alpha rhythm and an increase in beta.  Photic stimulation was performed as the patient was transitioning into stage II sleep with vertex waves and spindles.  Scant driving was noted.  Hyperventilation produces a small increase in amplitude of the background.
Heart rate irregular 90 beats per minute.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal EEG in wakefulness through stage II sleep.
CLINICAL CORRELATION:  No focal or epileptiform features were identified.  If epilepsy is an important consideration, a followup study may be of use.  In this individual with a recent episode with loss of consciousness and a 1 year history of blackout spells, additional EKG evaluation may be appropriate.

LENGTH OF THE RECORDING:  29 minutes.
CLINICAL HISTORY:  The patient is a 23-year-old man with a history of headaches and dizziness for 2 days as well as slight tremors.
MEDICATIONS:  Oxycodone, lorazepam, Tylenol, and Lovenox.
CONDITION OF THE RECORDING:  The recording was performed according to the standard 10-20 system with additional T1 and T2 electrodes and a single EKG lead.  Hyperventilation and photic stimulation were performed.
DESCRIPTION OF THE RECORDING:  The posterior dominant rhythm consists of well-formed and modulated 11 to 11.5 Hz alpha activity that attenuates with eyes opening.  There is an anterior to posterior frequency amplitude gradient with faster frequencies at low amplitudes anteriorly.  Excess diffuse beta is captured.  During sleep there are symmetrical and vertex waves, sleep spindles and K complexes were observed.   Hyperventilation is performed with good effort and results in mild diffuse background slowing.  Stepped photic stimulation does not result in any change in the background.
FINDINGS:
Stage 2 sleep.
No epileptiform discharges.
Excess beta.
IMPRESSION:  This is a normal awake and asleep 29 minute EEG.  The lack of epileptiform discharges on a routine EEG does not preclude a clinical diagnosis of epilepsy.  The excess beta could be secondary to medication effects such as benzodiazepines or barbiturates.
